metadata.name: Tally! #7921
metadata.description:
Tally! Is a year long, free, open edition to celebrate fxhash v2. Data from the minting of Tally! will be used to create other new artworks.

This artwork is simply about counting up from one to wherever we end up, with a litle bit of Fizz Buzz thrown in. Mints that have a prime numbers* as factors will have slight variations. Sometimes those variations will combine, sometimes you have to get to really high numbers for multiple prime numbers to combine.

Where the finally Tally! ends up who knows? But there's going to be a lot of tallying along the way, and it'll give you something to do while waiting between other mints.

INSTRUCTIONS ::

'?forceWidth=xxxx' on the end of the URL to change the width of the image
's' = save image

metadata.name: Mingle #11
metadata.description:
min·gle - mix or cause to mix together / move freely around a place or at a social function, associating with others.

Mingle is prose and code. Everything is circles. Sometimes you mingle together, sometimes you mingle apart.

* the animation takes time to trigger so you can read the generative prose, the animation eventually does end on a frame *

Just code (Javascript, no frameworks or dependencies).
Made by Dillan Simmons (dillansimmons.com)
https://objkt.com/profile/tz1Q4YfANpgKAuPXd1fobzBzdjg6wtPmmw5m/created

metadata.name: Blooming dancers #90
metadata.description:
Inspired by the similarity between a dancer's dress and a blooming flower.

It's an homage to art and nature, with exclusive features including :

- A choice between 12 modern and 12 rarer Artist inspired color palettes (Thanks to http://www.colorlisa.com/)
- 1 to 5 dancers
- Various Soft and Hard framing options
- A unique full canvas system which allows the collector to display on portrait, landscape or square screen the art
- A lot of line and background style variations.

The art is better viewed in full screen, captures don't display the fine details

patxol - 2022

Made with p5js

metadata.name: Watercolor Clouds #60
metadata.description: Points are generated based on a noise function, layers of color are added based on values from the same function.

metadata.name: Mirror Mirror #61
metadata.description:
Stare into the abyss with endlessly repeating forms twisting into the infinity defined by perlin randomness. This project is inspired by early childhood memories looking into two mirrors and playing with reflections forever.

Mirror Mirror is a generative project with a digital output, but it has a second life as a physical IRL object that can be cut from 12 layers of wood or plotted on paper.

24 free physicals will be attached at random to mints.
Learn more about physicals: https://alleditions.art/p/mirrormirror

SPECIAL FEATURES
- Shift-P: exports a PNG
- Shift-E: explodes the layers
- Shift-S: Exports an SVG
- A, S, D, & W: skew the layers
- ?screws=true: add some holes for Chicago screws

metadata.name: One Eleven (Defaced) #73
metadata.description: (Defaced) is the second installment of One Eleven, a periodical experiment.

metadata.name: Ataraxis #584
metadata.description:
Ataraxis (or a broken volume renderer) is an exploration in balancing discomfort and calm. The piece generates spaces on the fly that are designed to elicit strange and uncomfortable feelings - like a desolate, alien dreamscape - claustrophobic, surreal, not quite real yet strangely recognisable. But the idea is that while these spaces feel uncomfortable, they're also strangely, antilogically calming. The idea is to elicit a sanguine emotion, to make the viewer feel calm in a strange place, and to lead them somewhere else.

This work is the culmination of many years of work researching volumetric rendering techniques. This token uses a raymarching technique that is intentionally broken in various ways.

Controls:
Double-click to download
&w=X&h=y to change the size of the piece
&dpr=x to change the resolution of the pice - higher resolutions will result in slightly different artworks as the browser attempts to compensate for the overlarge canvas
&fullscreen=true to change the token to display the full size of your browser. This may impact the rendering of the token, so use with caution

metadata.name: Blockaden #462
metadata.description:
An exploration of patterns, destruction and overcoming.

/////

key "1" - "9": increases the render resolution by 2x with each step
-> These will automatically export a png after the simulation is done.

key "s": saves a png with the current resolution

metadata.name: Gravity's End #233
metadata.description:
Gravity's End depicts fictional worlds being warped, distorted, and in rare cases, shattered, due to extreme gravitational forces.

Gravity's End is written with shaders, so a gpu is recommended. It is very gpu friendly, in that only one frame is rendered.

Rarities

- 21 palettes with 5 rare palettes (4% chance for rare).
- 10% chance of getting a shattered world.

Keys: 

's' saves a png in the exact size of the screen.

metadata.name: Toupie-Néon #92
metadata.description:
Multicolor particles sampling space in 2D to give birth to 3D shapes in rotation.
Put any rythmic music you like and watch it in a dark room till your retina is printed with psychedelic patterns.

My most complex generator in the ideas yet the simplest in implementation & most unpredictable in the results with high diversity and peculiar rarities.
It's cheap because I'd like to see many variations of this generator so mint a lot ;)

You can navigate the scene, snapshot it, fly over it or just watch it.

WARNING: Webgl/GPU strongly advised for smoothness, CPU/mobile compliant with certainly heavy lag. 2K/4K/8K resolutions will burn your GPU ;)

Controls:
- H: hide/show help.
- Click/Move mouse - orbit control
- Dblclick/Space - start/pause animation.
- I: hide/show info panel. Click for panels (info, FPS).
- A-Q/D - resolution down/up (720p, 1080p, 2K, 4K, 8K)
- S - export full resolution pix (up to 8K)
- W-Z/C - rotation speede down/up
- F - fly mode on/off
- X/V - fly speed down/up

Toupie-Néon @naibdian 2022 using Opensource WebGL, ThreeJS libs, Inigo Quilez FBM noise functions.

metadata.name: bamboozle #18
metadata.description:
'bamboozle' by pixelwank 

bamboozle explores the shifting and warping that ones mental state goes through during a time of upset, ultimately leading to a better future. It is that positive state, post-shift, that the finished piece represents. 

tangled and wrangled over the course of the last year. 

press s to save png 
to render higher resolutions press 2,4,6,8, or g 
higher resolutions may be slower, thanks for waiting! 

thanks for collecting!

pixelwank 2023. 

r.i.f.f.

metadata.name: Here When You Need Me #60
metadata.description:
'Here When You Need Me' is a generative system that creates...

Good question, and I think the answer is up to you. Jewels? Reflections? The Sand in a Life's Hourglass?

Who knows. The truth is that I didn't have anything in mind for the project, and where it has ended up was purely through exploration, and a refinement of simple methods.

By the end, it has become exactly what I needed it to be, and the results of this project give me an encouragement that is difficult to explain.

Now, one of the primary features of the project is your ability to make it what you need. Several URL arguments are explained below that will allow you to tweak your edition's distortion and resolution.

15% of primary sales will be donated to 'Girls Who Code'
15% of primary sales will be donated to 'Cure Parkinson's'

10% of royalties will go to 'Girls Who Code'
10% of royalties will go to 'Cure Parkinson's'
10% of royalties will go to the original minter

Thank you everyone.


Options
-------
Parameters can be appended to the live URL to adjust the output's distortion, resolution, border size, and border color. These are all fun to play with, and can be used in combination to showcase the variability and potential of each piece.

'&distortion=#': Adjust distortion, any value from 0.0 to 3.0 (Use 0 to see a 'flat' version of the image)
'&resolution=#': Multiplier for width/height, any value from 0.1 to 6.0 (Soft max of 3.9)
'&borderSize=#': Multiplier for border size, any value from 0.0 to 3.0 (Use 0 for no border)
'&borderColor=ffffff': Custom border color, any 6 character hex code (Do not include '#')

An example of using multiple options would be '&resolution=2&distortion=.5'

Please check the linked fx(text) article for detailed examples on using these options.


Distortion
----------
I wanted to provide some amount of control to take advantage of the possibilities of generative art. 'Here When You Need Me' starts off at a certain point, but allows you to adjust the distortion to your favorite level.

Using '&distortion=0' will show the underlying shapes.


Resolution / Printing
---------------------
'Here When You Need Me' looks best with at least '&resolution=2' and is designed to support printing. Remember that parameters can be provided to adjust the border attributes as well.

Ideally, you should aim for 300 'pixels per inch' for a decent quality print. Default resolution is 1800x2400.

'&resolution=1' -> 6"x8"
'&resolution=2' -> 12"x16"

Some quick math will give you the correct modifier if you start with the width in inches of your desired print. 

(inches) * (ppi) / (default width)

An important note, the maximum resolution modifier I've had success with is 3.9 because of the browser's image size limitations, but the capability is still in the code to go higher in case it is helpful to someone.

If you have your edition printed, please share with me because it would make me incredibly happy to see it!


---------
Thank you to everyone for your support and contributions. 

I put way more detail in this description than I intended, but if you want even more, you can read about the development and potential of this project in the accompanying fx(text) article, once it is written.

Created by Walter Anderson (@noxiarb)

metadata.name: Reflections #123
metadata.description:
Reflections is a generative piece about four-fold symmetry and soft textures. Initially it was simply meant to be a successor to my very first Fxhash token ‘Furbol’, but it soon evolved into a lot more than that.

Press the down arrow key to save a .PNG of the token.
